00:19:04.830 --> 00:19:08.360
or turned a Civil War
song on its head.

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:10.990
But most Americans
felt, rather smugly,

00:19:10.990 --> 00:19:13.240
that they were above the war.

00:19:13.240 --> 00:19:17.040
A sentiment captured in two
songs by the novelty specialist,

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:19.850
Jack Frost and James White.

00:19:19.850 --> 00:19:25.600 position:56%
If They Want to Fight, sets a
stereotypical Germans and Brits side

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:31.780
by side with the prescient lyric,
I'm over here, they're over there.

00:19:31.780 --> 00:19:36.560
And in Neutrality Rag, Frost
plays several national anthems

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:38.000
against each other.

00:19:43.510 --> 00:21:42.510
[ Music ]

00:21:42.510 --> 00:21:50.010
[ Applause ]

00:21:50.010 --> 00:21:51.310
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee:

00:21:51.310 --> 00:21:52.960
The majority of Canadian
enlistees during the first year

00:21:52.960 --> 00:21:57.150
of the war were, in fact, not born
in Canada but in Europe, Britain,

00:21:57.150 --> 00:21:59.460
or other British and
European colonies.

00:21:59.460 --> 00:22:01.820
And many were veterans
of the Boar War.

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:03.970
Joseph Fairholme, Sr, for example,

00:22:03.970 --> 00:22:06.190
served in the British
Imperial Army Rifle Corp

00:22:06.190 --> 00:22:11.670
for 21 years before retiring
to a farm in Alberta in 1913.

00:22:11.670 --> 00:22:16.260
In November 1915, he enlisted in
the Canadian Expeditionary Force,

00:22:16.260 --> 00:22:20.780
or CEF, and was assigned to the
rank of Company Sergeant Master.

00:22:20.780 --> 00:22:24.070
Fairholme's two teenage
sons enlisted as well.

00:22:24.070 --> 00:22:26.270
The British character of
the Canadian armed forces

00:22:26.270 --> 00:22:29.390
in the first year of the war
explains a large part the slew

00:22:29.390 --> 00:22:31.780
of songs issued in
Canada and dedicated

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:34.690
to King George and the Union Jack.

00:22:34.690 --> 00:22:37.240
Canadian World War I
songs made common use

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:39.350
of imported British imagery,

00:22:39.350 --> 00:22:42.510
including easily recognizable
British tunes,

00:22:42.510 --> 00:22:46.490
such as Rule Britannia and God
Save the King, often in conjunction

00:22:46.490 --> 00:22:49.050
with British themed lyrics.

00:22:49.050 --> 00:22:52.240
Just as the Fairholmes enlisted
together based on close ties

00:22:52.240 --> 00:22:55.630
to Britain, the French
speaking Belaire brothers signed

00:22:55.630 --> 00:22:59.930 position:56%
up for military service that would
return them to a familiar landscape.

00:22:59.930 --> 00:23:04.090
Born in Geneva, Etienne, Andre,
and Phillipe Belaire immigrated

00:23:04.090 --> 00:23:05.850
with their parents
and other siblings

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:09.280
to a comfortable suburb
of Montreal in 1908.

00:23:09.280 --> 00:23:11.780
French speaking non-Quebecca
[assumed spelling] soldiers

00:23:11.780 --> 00:23:15.190
in the allied forces such as
the Belaire brothers were part

00:23:15.190 --> 00:23:19.910
of a large number of ex-patriots
from France, Switzerland, Belgium,

00:23:19.910 --> 00:23:24.190
and Francophone colonies, to enlist
during the first nine of the war.

00:23:24.190 --> 00:23:28.740
For whom a song such as Mon
Soldat served a recruiting role.

00:23:28.740 --> 00:23:32.850
The lyrics contained no hint
of empire, nor king, nor duty.

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:35.750
And little mention of
actually fighting the war.

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:38.770
Instead the song focuses on a
soldier's sweetheart promising

00:23:38.770 --> 00:23:42.090
to return to wait for
him until he returns.

00:23:42.090 --> 00:23:44.940
Notice as well, that the song
was published within Britain

00:23:44.940 --> 00:23:47.000
and distributed throughout Canada.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:50.770 position:56%
In this case, the Atlantic
Canadian province of News Brunswick,

00:23:50.770 --> 00:23:54.540
which had the largest Francophone
population outside of Quebec.

00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:56.440
The alternative English lyrics

00:23:56.440 --> 00:24:00.280
by contrast reinforced the
standard imperial tropes of duty,

00:24:00.280 --> 00:24:03.000
defeating the foe, and
fighting for the community.

00:24:07.510 --> 00:25:23.210
[ Music ]

00:25:23.210 --> 00:25:25.410
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: Like
Canadian songwriters,

00:25:25.410 --> 00:25:27.570
American composers
have always linked

00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:30.400
to their creations to
songs from the past.

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:33.920
And never more so than
during the Great War.

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:38.350
Iconography, too, built resonance
and cultural connections.

00:25:38.350 --> 00:25:41.270
A favorite image was of
the Statue of Liberty,

00:25:41.270 --> 00:25:43.650 position:56%
both because of its symbolic meaning

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:46.880
and because it embodied the
countries long-standing alliance

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:48.700
with France.

00:25:48.700 --> 00:25:53.380
Mothers inevitably were trundled
out as iconic representation

00:25:53.380 --> 00:25:57.850
of inspiration, nostalgia,
domesticity,

00:25:57.850 --> 00:26:01.390
or occasionally good sense.

00:26:01.390 --> 00:26:04.170
And musical quotations
were pervasive.

00:26:04.170 --> 00:26:06.860
Sometimes offering comment
on the subject matter,

00:26:06.860 --> 00:26:09.590
sometimes alluding to
other current hits.

00:26:09.590 --> 00:26:12.670
But most often, linking
the current conflict

00:26:12.670 --> 00:26:17.210
with wars America had
fought in the past.

00:26:17.210 --> 00:26:21.390
The first megahit of the war
brought all these strands together

00:26:21.390 --> 00:26:25.150
in an explicit refusal to fight.

00:26:25.150 --> 00:26:28.350
The cover puts mother, hearth,

00:26:28.350 --> 00:26:32.410
and an imaginary battle
scene in counterpoint.

00:26:32.410 --> 00:26:37.730
The title message is unmistakable
reinforced by the tag at the top,

00:26:37.730 --> 00:26:42.670
Ed Morton's sensational
anti-war song hit.

00:26:42.670 --> 00:26:45.970
The verse opens with a quotation

00:26:45.970 --> 00:26:48.830
from Thomas Moore's
The Minstrel Boy.

00:26:48.830 --> 00:26:52.060
The minstrel boy to
the war has gone .

00:26:52.060 --> 00:26:57.760
. . and follows that with a
quotation from Auld Lang Syne.

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:00.800
There is no question about
the political message here.

00:27:00.800 --> 00:27:04.580 position:56%
But not all Americans felt that way.

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:07.560
Even at the start of 1915.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:12.610
Just two months later Charles
Bayha wrote a rebuttal.

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:14.410
Bayha was pro-engagement.

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:16.030
He tried twice to enlist.

00:27:16.030 --> 00:27:18.670
And when he was rejected
he went to Camp Dix

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:22.490
and produced shows with
the soldiers there.

00:27:22.490 --> 00:27:26.100
Bayha's song is not as
powerful as Piantadose's

00:27:26.100 --> 00:27:28.700
and it had less impact at the time.

00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:34.630
But it makes clear the very real
conflict of opinion in the country.

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:36.000
Here's a sample of both songs.

00:27:40.510 --> 00:30:46.510
[ Music ]

00:30:46.510 --> 00:30:54.520
[ Applause ]

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:57.530
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: In Britain,
home-front anxiety emerged as early

00:30:57.530 --> 00:31:02.360
as 1915 when the first zeppelin
attacks brought casualties

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:05.210 position:56%
and destruction to towns and cities.

00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:08.120
Fears also arose for
civilian travel.

00:31:08.120 --> 00:31:11.010
When Germany declared the
waters around Britain a warzone

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:14.970
and began launching
torpedoes at allied ships.

00:31:14.970 --> 00:31:17.510
Simply on suspicion
of carrying war cargo.

00:31:17.510 --> 00:31:22.650
In 1915 the United States
was still officially neutral.

00:31:22.650 --> 00:31:25.570
But it was supplying food
and weapons to Britain,

00:31:25.570 --> 00:31:30.060
sometimes concealing them in
commercial passenger liners.

00:31:30.060 --> 00:31:34.050
Civilian sea travel started to
become a very risky undertaking.

00:31:34.050 --> 00:31:37.790
And after an American ship
sailing to France was attacked

00:31:37.790 --> 00:31:41.140
in April, jitters abounded.

00:31:41.140 --> 00:31:45.930
In May, as the luxury passenger
liner, the Lusitania prepared

00:31:45.930 --> 00:31:49.380
to set off on the return leg
of a round trip from Liverpool

00:31:49.380 --> 00:31:53.290
to New York, tension mounted.

00:31:53.290 --> 00:31:56.790 position:56%
Some newspapers published the German
Embassy's now prophetic warning

00:31:56.790 --> 00:32:00.680
of the potential dangers
for travelers.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:03.040
Some people delayed.

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:04.340
Most did not.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:09.540
And as the ship set off on May the
1st, carrying nearly 2,000 people,

00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:14.040
including Britains,
Canadians, and Americans.

00:32:14.040 --> 00:32:18.260
On the 7th of May, as the boat
skirted the south coast of Ireland,

00:32:18.260 --> 00:32:22.470
it was struck by a German
torpedo and sank rapidly.

00:32:22.470 --> 00:32:27.280
With the loss of nearly
1200 civilian lives.

00:32:27.280 --> 00:32:29.930
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee: An
estimated 360 Canadians or more

00:32:29.930 --> 00:32:32.360
than a quarter of the
total casualties were lost

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:34.420
in the sinking of the Lusitania.

00:32:34.420 --> 00:32:38.010
Many were wives and children of
British-Canadian soldiers training

00:32:38.010 --> 00:32:40.660
in England who looked
forward to renewing ties

00:32:40.660 --> 00:32:43.220
with extended families
still in Britain.

00:32:43.220 --> 00:32:44.520
Other Canadian travelers

00:32:44.520 --> 00:32:47.960
on the Lusitania were British
citizens living in Canada hoping

00:32:47.960 --> 00:32:50.320
to enlist in the British
army once they returned

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:52.200
to their country of origin.

00:32:52.200 --> 00:32:54.690
Immediately the Lusitania
became a rallying cry

00:32:54.690 --> 00:32:57.260
for the Canadian war effort.

00:32:57.260 --> 00:32:59.580 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: Most of
those who drowned were from Britain.

00:32:59.580 --> 00:33:02.580
Where the atmosphere in the days
following the atrocity was one

00:33:02.580 --> 00:33:04.240
of deep shock.

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:06.750
Several of the dead were
considerably wealthy.

00:33:06.750 --> 00:33:10.210
The ship being famed for
its opulent accommodations.

00:33:10.210 --> 00:33:12.420
And many of the fatalities
were women and children

00:33:12.420 --> 00:33:15.960
who had not been helped off
first as was the traditional code

00:33:15.960 --> 00:33:19.610
of conduct in maritime emergencies.

00:33:19.610 --> 00:33:27.410
Worst of all, most of the children
drowned, a shocking 91 out of 124.

00:33:27.410 --> 00:33:31.500
This figure included all six
children of Paul Crompton.

00:33:31.500 --> 00:33:34.400
A successful British businessman
who had been living and working

00:33:34.400 --> 00:33:38.630
in the U.S. and was
relocating his family to London.

00:33:38.630 --> 00:33:42.340
I tell you this because the
Crompton's are connected with one

00:33:42.340 --> 00:33:46.080
of the most poignant musical
responses to the tragedy.

00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:49.710
A short piece by the English
composer Frank Bridge.

00:33:49.710 --> 00:33:53.200
His Lament for String Orchestra.

00:33:53.200 --> 00:33:57.460
Written in June in 1915 in memory
of Crompton's 9-year-old daughter,

00:33:57.460 --> 00:34:00.670
Katherine, a well-loved
child friend.

00:34:00.670 --> 00:34:04.360
The Lament was performed at a
major London concert in September.

00:34:04.360 --> 00:34:07.110
But it attracted little
public attention.

00:34:07.110 --> 00:34:10.060
It's expression of
sorrow being out of sync

00:34:10.060 --> 00:34:13.250
with the more upbeat
mood of patriotism.

00:34:13.250 --> 00:34:15.600
Actually, the reporting
of the Cromptons' deaths

00:34:15.600 --> 00:34:17.810
in the British press was
fairly restrained, too.

00:34:17.810 --> 00:34:20.370
Compared to coverage
in American papers,

00:34:20.370 --> 00:34:22.090
which emphasized the tragic loss

00:34:22.090 --> 00:34:27.130
of an entire family including
a baby and its nanny.

00:34:27.130 --> 00:34:28.510
This poignant photograph

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:33.430
from a Philadelphia newspaper was
republished widely in the states.

00:34:33.430 --> 00:34:37.400
The piece itself is a
little gem of lamentation.

00:34:37.400 --> 00:34:41.790 position:56%
With downward chromatic emotion and
accented sighs in the violins melody

00:34:41.790 --> 00:34:44.830 position:56%
that emulate the pained human voice.

00:34:44.830 --> 00:34:48.230
As we listen, you may feel that
the rocking meter evokes the sea

00:34:48.230 --> 00:34:53.310
and the residence of the deep base
line conjures up the ocean's depth.

00:34:53.310 --> 00:34:56.250
Kevin Sultan has noted that
the swaying motion seems

00:34:56.250 --> 00:34:58.600
to suggest a lullaby.

00:34:58.600 --> 00:35:02.190 position:56%
We might further position this piece
in the cross-cultural tradition

00:35:02.190 --> 00:35:05.310
of what has been termed
the lullament.

00:35:05.310 --> 00:35:10.060
Music of mourning that
integrates elements of lullaby.

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:12.080
In fact, that's highly
appropriate for a work

00:35:12.080 --> 00:35:14.510
that commemorated the
death of a child and one

00:35:14.510 --> 00:35:17.050
that could symbolize
the children of all ages

00:35:17.050 --> 00:35:19.960
and nationalities who
drowned that day.

00:35:19.960 --> 00:35:23.590
Moreover, with its
Anglo-American subject matter

00:35:23.590 --> 00:35:27.190
and its public performance
by a large string assemble,

00:35:27.190 --> 00:35:33.120
the Lament seems with hindsight
a British gesture of solidarity

00:35:33.120 --> 00:35:35.000
and grief with North America.

00:35:39.510 --> 00:37:29.010
[ Music ]

00:37:29.010 --> 00:37:32.250
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: The United
States lost fewer people

00:37:32.250 --> 00:37:34.660
on the Lusitania than did Britain.

00:37:34.660 --> 00:37:37.980
But the shock was far greater.

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:40.530
The country had imagined
itself safe,

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:46.070
protected by distance
and by neutrality.

00:37:46.070 --> 00:37:48.770
Now clearly it was vulnerable.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:55.240
The war had come home, and
death had touched the country.

00:37:55.240 --> 00:37:57.960
Tin Pan Alley reacted
with two songs published

00:37:57.960 --> 00:38:00.030
within two weeks of the tragedy.

00:38:00.030 --> 00:38:03.430
But neither of these attained
the status of a true memorial

00:38:03.430 --> 00:38:05.760
or expression of the
country's grief.

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:10.970
That task was undertaken
by Charles Ives.

00:38:10.970 --> 00:38:16.030
Who composed an orchestral work,
From Hannover Square North,

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:22.400
at the end of a tragic day the
voice of the people again arose

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:24.070
in the months that followed.

00:38:24.070 --> 00:38:28.610
The piece is an impression
of an incident

00:38:28.610 --> 00:38:32.450
that Ives witnessed
the day the news broke.

00:38:32.450 --> 00:38:34.800
And his description is remarkable.

00:38:34.800 --> 00:38:40.130
&gt;&gt; Justin Vickers: Leaving the
office, I took the Third Avenue L

00:38:40.130 --> 00:38:42.410
at Hannover Square Station.

00:38:42.410 --> 00:38:45.070
As I came on the platform
there was quite a crowd waiting

00:38:45.070 --> 00:38:46.500
for the trains.

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:50.970
And a hand organ where Hurdy Gurdy
was playing in the street below.

00:38:50.970 --> 00:38:52.270
Some workmen sitting on the side

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:54.810
of the tracks began
to whistle the tune.

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:58.520
And others began to
sing or hum the refrain.

00:38:58.520 --> 00:39:02.710
A workman with a shovel over his
shoulder joined in the chorus.

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:07.060
And the next pan the Wall
Street Banker joined in.

00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:12.220
And finally, it seemed to me that
everyone was singling this tune.

00:39:12.220 --> 00:39:20.380
And they didn't seem
to be singing in fun.

00:39:20.380 --> 00:39:21.680
But as a natural sound
of what they're feeling

00:39:21.680 --> 00:39:23.480
as they [inaudible] all day long.

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:58.050
[ Music ]

00:39:58.050 --> 00:40:03.270
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: Ives
perfectly captured the crisis.

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:08.720
Not merely of war and peace but
of the country's very identity.

00:40:08.720 --> 00:40:12.420
He reacted as a Wilsonian
idealist with a faith

00:40:12.420 --> 00:40:16.950
that all factions would come
together, workmen and banker,

00:40:16.950 --> 00:40:22.590
rich and poor, immigrants
and native born.

00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:26.120
But events would overtake him.

00:40:27.780 --> 00:40:32.710
After the Lusitania, Wilson moved
very carefully, squeezed as he was

00:40:32.710 --> 00:40:35.870
between militants like
Theodore Roosevelt and advocates

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:41.860 position:56%
of neutrality which included the
majority of Congress and the nation.

00:40:41.860 --> 00:40:45.430 position:56%
His primary policy was preparedness.

00:40:45.430 --> 00:40:48.030
The nation would get
ready for war but seek

00:40:48.030 --> 00:40:51.750
to avoid it, if at all possible.

00:40:51.750 --> 00:40:54.540
This campaign also
had musical results.

00:40:54.540 --> 00:40:57.790
But the great consequence was
that Wilson managed to squeak

00:40:57.790 --> 00:41:01.830
through the 1916 election by
promoting himself as the man

00:41:01.830 --> 00:41:04.350
who kept the country out of war.

00:41:04.350 --> 00:41:10.250
In 1917, however, things
quickly turned ugly.

00:41:10.250 --> 00:41:13.170
At the beginning of February,

00:41:13.170 --> 00:41:17.900
Germany announced it was resuming
unrestricted submarine warfare.

00:41:17.900 --> 00:41:21.980
And in March, the so-called
Zimmerman telegram was made public,

00:41:21.980 --> 00:41:23.790
in which Germany proposed
an alliance

00:41:23.790 --> 00:41:26.570
with Mexico suggesting
another border war

00:41:26.570 --> 00:41:30.160
to keep the United
States busy at home.

00:41:30.160 --> 00:41:34.250
American sentiment shifted
overwhelmingly to the Allies

00:41:34.250 --> 00:41:42.240
and on April 6, 1917 the United
States officially entered the war.

00:41:42.240 --> 00:41:45.540
There followed a great
up swell of patriotism.

00:41:45.540 --> 00:41:49.820
Manifested musically in
George M. Cohan's Over There,

00:41:49.820 --> 00:41:54.170
allegedly written in a couple of
hours the day after the U.S. entry.

00:41:54.170 --> 00:41:57.000
We see it here in a later edition

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:00.640
with a famous cover
created by Norman Rockwell.

00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:04.160
But Over There was a
harbinger of times to come,

00:42:04.160 --> 00:42:08.820
in that it was popularized as much
by recordings as by sheet music.

00:42:08.820 --> 00:42:13.460
First off the mark was
the American quartet.

00:42:13.460 --> 00:42:18.160 position:56%
Followed a week later by Nora Bayes,
who was pictured on an early cover.

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:23.890
But the most remarkable recording
was made by legendary tenor

00:42:23.890 --> 00:42:29.860
and Enrico Caruso who recorded
two verses in two languages.

00:42:29.860 --> 00:42:35.380
This disc of a song written
by an Irish-American,

00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:39.130
recorded by an Italian
singing in English

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:43.970
and in French was hugely
successful in the United States,

00:42:43.970 --> 00:42:47.970
Britain, Canada, and Australia.

00:42:47.970 --> 00:42:50.380 position:56%
There was no better musical instance

00:42:50.380 --> 00:42:52.510
of the alliance that
had been formed.

00:42:52.510 --> 00:45:39.650
[ Music ]

00:45:39.650 --> 00:45:46.550
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: As early as
1915, the popular music industry

00:45:46.550 --> 00:45:50.330 position:56%
in Britain moved beyond its
patriotic role as a recruiter of men

00:45:50.330 --> 00:45:54.230
to buoy up spirits both at
home and further afield.

00:45:54.230 --> 00:45:56.840
Publishers mailed sheet
music to troops stations

00:45:56.840 --> 00:46:00.560
or training camps where, with
the aid of an upright piano

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:04.110
that had been commandeered
locally and a willing pianist,

00:46:04.110 --> 00:46:08.920 position:56%
soldiers' morale could be maintained
and boredom averted through song.

00:46:08.920 --> 00:46:12.470
Men who had brought instruments
from home, a cornet, a violin,

00:46:12.470 --> 00:46:15.710
a banjo, might join in, too.

00:46:15.710 --> 00:46:18.750
Phonograph companies likewise
supplied free recordings

00:46:18.750 --> 00:46:20.090
of wartime hits.

00:46:20.090 --> 00:46:22.170
And entertainers were
ushered off to Flanders

00:46:22.170 --> 00:46:25.080
to help keep up soldiers' spirits.

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:28.440
Some of the performers were
well known musical personalities

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:32.530
such as the singer Harry Lauder
celebrated for his comic routines

00:46:32.530 --> 00:46:35.800
and performance of
stereotypical Scottishness.

00:46:35.800 --> 00:46:41.790 position:56%
Also, important to the story is Lena
Ashwell, a key figure in setting

00:46:41.790 --> 00:46:44.210
up entertainments for the troops.

00:46:44.210 --> 00:46:47.630
Already famed as a
Shakespearean actor and a supporter

00:46:47.630 --> 00:46:51.500
of women's rights, she campaigned
strongly during the wars early

00:46:51.500 --> 00:46:54.820
months for the creation
of touring programs.

00:46:54.820 --> 00:46:57.510
She raised considerable
sums of money to fund them.

00:46:57.510 --> 00:47:00.130
And she also got the YMCA involved.

00:47:00.130 --> 00:47:02.890
Promoting and improving
diet of accessible items

00:47:02.890 --> 00:47:07.210
of classical music alongside
recitations and group singing.

00:47:07.210 --> 00:47:10.900
Most of these concert
parties, as they were known,

00:47:10.900 --> 00:47:13.280
performed well back
behind the lines.

00:47:13.280 --> 00:47:16.280
And they, no doubt, provided relief
for soldiers who had been there

00:47:16.280 --> 00:47:18.850
for weeks without a break.

00:47:18.850 --> 00:47:20.220
But when the momen
[assumed spelling] moved

00:47:20.220 --> 00:47:23.500
up to the trenches life
was very different.

00:47:23.500 --> 00:47:25.720
As was any music making.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:27.860
Instruments were few.

00:47:27.860 --> 00:47:29.420
One British private recanted.

00:47:29.420 --> 00:47:34.160
&gt;&gt; Jeffrey Dukes: There'd
be times when you would sit

00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:38.370
around on the firestop, the
lads would talk and sing.

00:47:38.370 --> 00:47:41.540
We had one chap who was
a very, very good singer.

00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:45.390 position:56%
And he used to indulge in his
singing and lead us in the choruses.

00:47:45.390 --> 00:47:48.490
And he was always inclined
to get a bit sentimental.

00:47:48.490 --> 00:47:50.410
We had to shut him up
for obvious reasons

00:47:50.410 --> 00:47:56.760
as we couldn't stand
too much of that.

00:47:56.760 --> 00:47:59.150
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: With
sentimentality to be avoided,

00:47:59.150 --> 00:48:03.570
clever parodies of popular
songs proved much more the norm.

00:48:03.570 --> 00:48:07.810
It's a Long Way to Tipperary
famously became It's the Wrong Way

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:10.500
to Tickle Mary.

00:48:10.500 --> 00:48:13.550
Yet most soldier songs
were far more graphic.

00:48:13.550 --> 00:48:17.230
The book of Tommy's Tunes compiled
by Frederick Thomas Nettleingham

00:48:17.230 --> 00:48:20.490
and published in 1917
gives many glimpses

00:48:20.490 --> 00:48:24.480
of the psychological reality
of being on active service.

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:27.590
Numbers such as I Don't
Want to Be a Soldier,

00:48:27.590 --> 00:48:31.030
or I Want to Go Home are
complemented by others

00:48:31.030 --> 00:48:35.720
that are glossed with
sarcasm or biting satire.

00:48:35.720 --> 00:48:39.040
Church of England hymns became
especially favorite targets

00:48:39.040 --> 00:48:40.480
for parody.

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:43.960
An apt means of attacking
the establishment credo

00:48:43.960 --> 00:48:48.000
but wartime sacrifice was
all for God and country.

00:48:51.510 --> 00:49:43.110
[ Music ]

00:49:43.110 --> 00:49:44.410
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee:
Canadian troops struggled

00:49:44.410 --> 00:49:45.710
to keep up morale, too.

00:49:45.710 --> 00:49:49.190
And began creating their own
concert parties on the front lines.

00:49:49.190 --> 00:49:54.170
The most famous comedy troop was
The Dumbells formed in mid-1917

00:49:54.170 --> 00:49:57.950
from active duty soldiers
in the CEFs third division.

00:49:57.950 --> 00:50:01.270
A typical Dumbell variety
show featured wartime hits

00:50:01.270 --> 00:50:05.870 position:56%
such as It's a Long Way to Tipperary
alongside send ups of military life.

00:50:05.870 --> 00:50:08.520
After the war, the
Dumbells would find fame

00:50:08.520 --> 00:50:11.430
in London's West End
and on Broadway.

00:50:11.430 --> 00:50:15.830 position:56%
Other Canadian entertainers included
Nova Scotia born Lieutenant Gitz

00:50:15.830 --> 00:50:19.610
Rice who performed as singer
and pianist in concert parties,

00:50:19.610 --> 00:50:22.290
in addition to his
duties as a soldier.

00:50:22.290 --> 00:50:24.860
Rice's musical training
at the McGill Conservatory

00:50:24.860 --> 00:50:28.480
in Montreal along with his
firsthand military experience

00:50:28.480 --> 00:50:32.600
as a gunnery officer inspired
his work as a songwriter.

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:35.340
Rice's songs achieved
widespread fame in Canada

00:50:35.340 --> 00:50:37.360
and the United States, especially

00:50:37.360 --> 00:50:40.070
after the American
entry into the war.

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:43.520
His most successful song
was Dear Old Pal of Mine.

00:50:43.520 --> 00:50:47.050
Which he wrote while on duty
in Ypres and which became a hit

00:50:47.050 --> 00:50:49.600
in sheet music and recordings.

00:50:49.600 --> 00:50:53.870
During the Battle of Vimy Ridge
on April 9 through 12, 1917,

00:50:53.870 --> 00:50:57.260
Rice was gassed along with
thousands of Canadian soldiers.

00:50:57.260 --> 00:50:59.640
He was discharged from
the CEF and worked

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:01.980
in Vaudeville through the 1920s.

00:51:01.980 --> 00:51:07.260
He died at age 56 in 1947 of
complications from bronchial asthma

00:51:07.260 --> 00:51:09.540
and long-term damage to his lungs.

00:51:09.540 --> 00:51:13.750
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: In the United
States enlisted vaudevillians

00:51:13.750 --> 00:51:16.270
and musicians produced
entertainments both

00:51:16.270 --> 00:51:19.270
at home and abroad.

00:51:19.270 --> 00:51:22.930
Possibly the most famous musical
soldier was Irving Berlin,

00:51:22.930 --> 00:51:27.170
whose score and performance in
Yip, Yip Yaphank was seen first

00:51:27.170 --> 00:51:30.980
in a New Jersey training
camp in summer 1918.

00:51:30.980 --> 00:51:35.150
And then before and after
the armistice on Broadway.

00:51:35.150 --> 00:51:39.580
Nearer to the action,
though, was Elsie Janis.

00:51:39.580 --> 00:51:43.060
A vaudeville star who not
only entertained the troops

00:51:43.060 --> 00:51:48.340 position:56%
but incorporated ex-soldiers into
her review Elsie Janis and Her Gang,

00:51:48.340 --> 00:51:52.100
which ran for over three
years in various venues.

00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:57.790
In Europe, however, the unexpected
musical stars were African-American

00:51:57.790 --> 00:51:59.960
soldiers and ensembles.

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:05.070
Most famously, James Reese
Europe's Hellfighters Band.

00:52:05.070 --> 00:52:08.920
Like Francophones in Canadian
and the Irish in Britain,

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:12.320 position:56%
African-Americans would take a
large step on the road to acceptance

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:15.490
and respect during the Great War.

00:52:15.490 --> 00:52:18.530
Although initially Wilson's
administration avoided recruiting

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:23.090
African-Americans, and although
African-American regimens never

00:52:23.090 --> 00:52:27.930
served under American officers,
their troops fought with the French

00:52:27.930 --> 00:52:33.100
and compiled a remarkable
record of service and valor.

00:52:33.100 --> 00:52:35.050
James Reese Europe had enlisted

00:52:35.050 --> 00:52:38.260
in the National Guard even
before the American entry

00:52:38.260 --> 00:52:41.500
on September 18, 1916.

00:52:41.500 --> 00:52:44.220
He assembled a band of
remarkable musicians

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:47.470
and the music they made caused
a sensation when they appeared

00:52:47.470 --> 00:52:51.940
in France on New Year's Day 1918.

00:52:51.940 --> 00:52:53.920
The stylistic innovations that he

00:52:53.920 --> 00:52:58.740 position:56%
and other African-Americans produced
would transform popular music

00:52:58.740 --> 00:53:03.950
in the post war decade in
America as well as France.

00:53:03.950 --> 00:53:06.250
Gone was Ragtime.

00:53:06.250 --> 00:53:09.100
In its place, Jazz.

00:53:09.100 --> 00:53:11.960
Gone were mournful ballads.

00:53:11.960 --> 00:53:15.310
In their place the Blues.

00:53:15.310 --> 00:53:18.980
Even more importantly,
gone were coon songs

00:53:18.980 --> 00:53:22.600
and the most despicable
of racial stereotypes.

00:53:22.600 --> 00:53:25.720
In their place arose the
beginnings of dignity

00:53:25.720 --> 00:53:28.380
and honor for people of color.

00:53:28.380 --> 00:53:33.710
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: By the
time the U.S. entered the war,

00:53:33.710 --> 00:53:37.530
Britain was fully operating
under wartime conditions.

00:53:37.530 --> 00:53:39.830
Right from the start, the
government had taken control

00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:43.670
of its citizens lives,
mobilizing a mass male army,

00:53:43.670 --> 00:53:49.090
initially through volunteers,
and from 1916 by conscription.

00:53:49.090 --> 00:53:53.300
Along side came a reconfiguration
of Britain's industrial economy.

00:53:53.300 --> 00:53:57.010
As women took jobs in factories
or worked with munitions,

00:53:57.010 --> 00:54:02.370
communication, farming, nursing,
and other war effort duties.

00:54:02.370 --> 00:54:04.340
Encouraged by national advertising

00:54:04.340 --> 00:54:08.760
and the temporary dissolving
of gender stereotypes.

00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:12.910
In the musical world the empty
chairs in orchestras created

00:54:12.910 --> 00:54:16.860
as men went to war were
temporarily taken over by women

00:54:16.860 --> 00:54:20.970
who had long been denied such
professional opportunity.

00:54:20.970 --> 00:54:23.110 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee: In Canada
government censorship controlled the

00:54:23.110 --> 00:54:25.760
publication and distribution
of sheet music.

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:29.050
Authorized songs reflected the
official narrative of progress

00:54:29.050 --> 00:54:33.160
from colony to nation and to a
unified anglophone Canadian culture

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:35.030
loyal to British rule.

00:54:35.030 --> 00:54:37.490
These songs served to
recruit the army's volunteers

00:54:37.490 --> 00:54:40.550
and to build popular
support for the war at home.

00:54:40.550 --> 00:54:43.890
Criticism of the war and realistic
representations of suffering

00:54:43.890 --> 00:54:46.270
by Canadian soldiers
were not allowed,

00:54:46.270 --> 00:54:49.060
at least during the first
few years of the conflict.

00:54:49.060 --> 00:54:53.210
And official reports of the
war were relentlessly positive.

00:54:53.210 --> 00:54:57.070 position:56%
On the home front, families were
encouraged to write cheerful letters

00:54:57.070 --> 00:54:59.710
to soldiers in training
and on the front lines.

00:54:59.710 --> 00:55:02.330
For their part, soldiers
tried to make light of life

00:55:02.330 --> 00:55:04.220
in the trenches in letters home.

00:55:04.220 --> 00:55:07.240
Even as their private journals
expressed the harsh reality

00:55:07.240 --> 00:55:09.000
of the western front.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.020
These documents reflect
a personalization

00:55:11.020 --> 00:55:13.670
of public discourse
concerning the war effort.

00:55:13.670 --> 00:55:19.830
A denial of the horrors of war in
all but the most private spaces.

00:55:19.830 --> 00:55:22.500
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: June 6, 1916.

00:55:22.500 --> 00:55:26.140
Dear Mother, you have probably
received my card telling you

00:55:26.140 --> 00:55:27.950
that I was wounded.

00:55:27.950 --> 00:55:29.910
It's happily nothing very serious.

00:55:29.910 --> 00:55:31.850
And I think that I will
be cured in a week.

00:55:31.850 --> 00:55:33.150
Andre.

00:55:38.820 --> 00:55:41.150
&gt;&gt; Justin Vickers: July 20, 1917.

00:55:41.150 --> 00:55:44.410
My Dear Parents, I am writing
to you from a little paradise

00:55:44.410 --> 00:55:47.500
where we are resting after
a stint in the trenches.

00:55:47.500 --> 00:55:50.120
Our camp is set up in a
field completely surrounded

00:55:50.120 --> 00:55:53.190
by a beautiful forest
in the French style.

00:55:53.190 --> 00:55:55.700
Hardly touched by the bombardments.

00:55:55.700 --> 00:55:59.250
It is so restful to be in a
normal corner of the country.

00:55:59.250 --> 00:56:00.550
Phillipe.

00:56:00.550 --> 00:56:05.540 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Laurie Matheson: August 29, 1918.

00:56:05.540 --> 00:56:10.720
My Dear Boys, We will read a few
short verses from the big Bible

00:56:10.720 --> 00:56:14.830
and pray for the victory that may
follow the uninterrupted march

00:56:14.830 --> 00:56:16.650
that we have just read about.

00:56:16.650 --> 00:56:20.870
And we also pray for the European
families that we love so much.

00:56:20.870 --> 00:56:23.370
And especially for our soldiers.

00:56:23.370 --> 00:56:27.570
We are presuming that the Canadian
advance is giving the topographers

00:56:27.570 --> 00:56:31.880
so much work that Andre
finds it impossible to write.

00:56:31.880 --> 00:56:33.400
Mother.

00:56:33.400 --> 00:56:35.760
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee: Privately
soldiers recorded a different

00:56:35.760 --> 00:56:37.360
version of their experiences.

00:56:37.360 --> 00:56:42.690
&gt;&gt; William Brooks:
December 16, 2916.

00:56:42.690 --> 00:56:44.890
We had quite a night
of it in the barn.

00:56:44.890 --> 00:56:51.420
It was cold and the rates
danced over us all night.

00:56:51.420 --> 00:56:54.170
April 12, 1917.

00:56:54.170 --> 00:56:56.460
Mud up to our thighs.

00:56:56.460 --> 00:56:58.230
I've had no sleep whatsoever.

00:56:58.230 --> 00:57:03.430
October 31,1917.

00:57:03.430 --> 00:57:08.000
I shall ever remember
the Hell we went through.

00:57:12.130 --> 00:57:13.790
The United States entered the war

00:57:13.790 --> 00:57:15.990
with a great show of
collective resolve.

00:57:15.990 --> 00:57:19.460
But the country quickly
began to divide.

00:57:19.460 --> 00:57:22.920
On the one hand, there were great
national campaigns for support.

00:57:22.920 --> 00:57:29.430
Manifested especially by promoting
a series of Liberty Loans support

00:57:29.430 --> 00:57:32.940
for which transcended
class and region.

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:35.980
These were boosted by
promotional music written not only

00:57:35.980 --> 00:57:41.260
by Tin Pan Alley but by locals
like Earl Threlkeld of Charleston,

00:57:41.260 --> 00:57:46.060
Illinois, whose Buy a Bond was
adopted as an official song

00:57:46.060 --> 00:57:49.260 position:56%
of the Fourth Liberty Loan campaign.

00:57:49.260 --> 00:57:53.580
Publications like this produced by
people living in small communities

00:57:53.580 --> 00:57:56.100
and motivated in large
part by patriotism

00:57:56.100 --> 00:58:00.430
or civic duty played a large
part in home front displays

00:58:00.430 --> 00:58:03.630
of support for the troops.

00:58:03.630 --> 00:58:06.590
Such support was actively
promoted by government agencies

00:58:06.590 --> 00:58:10.380
like George Creel's committee
on public information

00:58:10.380 --> 00:58:15.020 position:56%
which produced posters, issues
press releases, and recruited a corp

00:58:15.020 --> 00:58:20.680
of Four-Minute Men who boosted
morale at rallies and in theaters.

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:23.680
Creel's committee also sponsored
music in training camps run

00:58:23.680 --> 00:58:28.440
by professional musicians and with
an approved uplifting repertoire.

00:58:28.440 --> 00:58:32.980
But Creel's committee had
a darker side as well.

00:58:32.980 --> 00:58:37.080
One that reflected a see
change in American culture.

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:41.810
The country was coming apart
despite the forced show of unity.

00:58:41.810 --> 00:58:45.280
Americans began to view
each other with suspicion.

00:58:45.280 --> 00:58:48.920
German-Americans, in particular,
were forced out of jobs

00:58:48.920 --> 00:58:52.520 position:56%
and isolated from wider communities.

00:58:52.520 --> 00:58:56.480
Now, there were two
views about foreigners.

00:58:56.480 --> 00:59:00.640
On the one hand, the United States
continued to think of itself

00:59:00.640 --> 00:59:04.660
as a refuge, give me
your tired, the poor,

00:59:04.660 --> 00:59:08.060
your huddled masses
yearning to be free.

00:59:08.060 --> 00:59:13.940
But on the other, vigilante groups
sanctioned by the government began

00:59:13.940 --> 00:59:17.870
to persecute immigrant
and ethnic minorities.

00:59:17.870 --> 00:59:22.390
At times government interventions
constituted censorship,

00:59:22.390 --> 00:59:23.920
pure and simple.

00:59:23.920 --> 00:59:29.960
Just after the war was declared two
obscure songwriters in New Jersey,

00:59:29.960 --> 00:59:34.830
Joseph Woodruff and E.J. Pourmon
self-published After the War is

00:59:34.830 --> 00:59:38.440
Over Will There Be
any Home Sweet Home?

00:59:38.440 --> 00:59:43.190
With disturbing lyrics and
an equally disturbing cover.

00:59:43.190 --> 00:59:47.120
The song became locally popular and
later that year it was purchased

00:59:47.120 --> 00:59:51.740
by the Joe Morris Music
Company, a major New York firm.

00:59:51.740 --> 00:59:56.520
Morris reissued it, dressed up
with slightly softened lyrics

00:59:56.520 --> 00:59:58.760
and its popularity continued.

00:59:58.760 --> 01:00:02.660
But in spring 1918, the
song came to the attention

01:00:02.660 --> 01:00:06.770
of the army's military intelligence
division and as reported

01:00:06.770 --> 01:00:11.350
by author Rupert Hughes, Joe
Morris' patriotism was appealed to

01:00:11.350 --> 01:00:15.320
and as a result he promptly
changed the words to others

01:00:15.320 --> 01:00:18.810
of a more inspiring
and cheerful nature.

01:00:18.810 --> 01:00:24.560
He also deleted the title tag
and replaced the cover image.

01:00:24.560 --> 01:00:28.930
And in it's new upbeat version,
After the War is Over was printed

01:00:28.930 --> 01:00:32.520 position:56%
and reprinted to the end of the war.

01:00:32.520 --> 01:00:35.230
Justin and Jeff will give
us both versions now.

01:00:35.230 --> 01:00:39.680
First the original as
self-published in April 1917.

01:00:39.680 --> 01:00:43.470
And then the more inspiring
and cheerful song

01:00:43.470 --> 01:00:45.000
that the government imposed.

01:00:51.510 --> 01:04:01.510
[ Music ]

01:04:01.510 --> 01:04:11.990
[ Applause ]

01:04:11.990 --> 01:04:13.290
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: In and out

01:04:13.290 --> 01:04:16.810
of the British trenches despite
the dankness and squalor,

01:04:16.810 --> 01:04:19.500
verse of another sort came to life.

01:04:19.500 --> 01:04:24.340 position:56%
Some of it was written by amateurs
who made forays into poetry clinging

01:04:24.340 --> 01:04:27.590
to religion or patriotism
as a means of coping

01:04:27.590 --> 01:04:30.170
with their military assignments.

01:04:30.170 --> 01:04:34.700
As with this one, later printed
privately for the soldier's family,

01:04:34.700 --> 01:04:37.000
which you can see for
yourself on the screen.

01:04:44.100 --> 01:04:46.190
But the most famous
of the soldier poets,

01:04:46.190 --> 01:04:48.800
when they entered the military,
were already living lives

01:04:48.800 --> 01:04:53.080
through the written word, teaching
English, publishing poetry, essays,

01:04:53.080 --> 01:04:57.020
novels, working as
journalists, and so forth.

01:04:57.020 --> 01:04:59.860
Today enshrined as the war poets,

01:04:59.860 --> 01:05:03.850
this group includes Siegfried
Sassoon, Edward Thomas,

01:05:03.850 --> 01:05:06.960
Rupert Brooke, Wilfred
Owen, and Isaac Rosenberg.

01:05:06.960 --> 01:05:11.870
And their work vividly communicates
the mix of fear, routine,

01:05:11.870 --> 01:05:16.170
and searing horror that they
experienced on the front line.

01:05:16.170 --> 01:05:18.000
Again, you can see some
of it on the screens.

01:05:28.540 --> 01:05:32.900
Musicians signed up to serve
their King and country, too.

01:05:32.900 --> 01:05:36.230
Many of them were on the
threshold of significant careers.

01:05:36.230 --> 01:05:39.690
Such as the young classical
composers George Butterworth,

01:05:39.690 --> 01:05:44.080
Arthur Bliss, Cecil
Coles, and Iver Gurney.

01:05:44.080 --> 01:05:47.710
All fought, some were killed.

01:05:47.710 --> 01:05:52.200
The older Ralph Vaughn Williams
volunteered for the medical corp

01:05:52.200 --> 01:05:55.130
and was deeply disturbed
by the experience.

01:05:55.130 --> 01:05:58.530
In practical terms, writing music

01:05:58.530 --> 01:06:01.860
in the trenches was much more
challenging than writing poetry.

01:06:01.860 --> 01:06:05.670
In as much as it required
special paper and a certain amount

01:06:05.670 --> 01:06:09.900
of silence if not a
piano within reach.

01:06:09.900 --> 01:06:12.770
As a result, most war
pieces were composed

01:06:12.770 --> 01:06:15.560
after the conflict had ended.

01:06:15.560 --> 01:06:17.570
With a few exceptions.

01:06:17.570 --> 01:06:21.690
Coles was working on an orchestral
suite entitled Behind the Lines

01:06:21.690 --> 01:06:23.230
when he died.

01:06:23.230 --> 01:06:26.170
He had sent its third movement
back to his friend and mentor

01:06:26.170 --> 01:06:27.960
in England, Gustav Holts.

01:06:27.960 --> 01:06:32.580
Then there was the
brilliant Iver Gurney

01:06:32.580 --> 01:06:35.750
who was both poet and composer.

01:06:35.750 --> 01:06:39.100
In France he produced poems as
well as a few songs settings.

01:06:39.100 --> 01:06:42.440
Though he is experiences of war
would soon unravel through injuries

01:06:42.440 --> 01:06:44.250
into serious mental collapse.

01:06:44.250 --> 01:06:48.120
And he would write most of
his war induced art songs

01:06:48.120 --> 01:06:52.640
in an asylum back in
post-war Britain.

01:06:52.640 --> 01:06:54.470
Gurney's songs from
the front are imbued

01:06:54.470 --> 01:06:58.680
with poignant pastoral yearnings
for his native Gloucester.

01:06:58.680 --> 01:07:01.790
But there are also traces
of anger and revulsion

01:07:01.790 --> 01:07:05.020
at what was happening around him.

01:07:05.020 --> 01:07:09.640
His powerful setting of John
Masefield's By a Bierside,

01:07:09.640 --> 01:07:15.640
written in a disused trench
mortar emplacement in August 1916

01:07:15.640 --> 01:07:20.320
and a spell away from front line
duty puts the soldier's distress

01:07:20.320 --> 01:07:21.620
center stage.

01:07:28.510 --> 01:11:30.510
[ Music ]

01:11:30.510 --> 01:11:40.330
[ Applause ]

01:11:40.330 --> 01:11:42.770
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee: Canada
had its own war poet as well.

01:11:42.770 --> 01:11:46.370
An obscure physician from
the small town of Guelph.

01:11:46.370 --> 01:11:50.980
In late April 1915, Canada's First
Division fought alongside French

01:11:50.980 --> 01:11:53.950
and British troops at the
second battle of Ypres.

01:11:53.950 --> 01:11:57.670
And as was reported in the British
and Canadian press, the untested

01:11:57.670 --> 01:12:00.830
but tenacious Canadians
performed valiantly.

01:12:00.830 --> 01:12:03.290
Despite the division
having more British veterans

01:12:03.290 --> 01:12:06.440
than Canadian born soldiers,
the victory became part

01:12:06.440 --> 01:12:09.510
of national lore almost
immediately with accolades

01:12:09.510 --> 01:12:13.790
by British leadership praising the
"grand colonial type of manhood

01:12:13.790 --> 01:12:16.890
that we now recognize as
the cream of the race."

01:12:16.890 --> 01:12:22.380 position:56%
Behind the public relations campaign
that emphasized glory and sacrifice,

01:12:22.380 --> 01:12:25.080
the CEF suffered horrific losses.

01:12:25.080 --> 01:12:28.420
Around a third of the divisions
18,000 men were killed,

01:12:28.420 --> 01:12:30.090
wounded, or missing.

01:12:30.090 --> 01:12:35.000 position:56%
With many casualties resulting from
the war's first use of chlorine gas.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:36.300
The battle inspired one

01:12:36.300 --> 01:12:39.640
of the Canadian brigade's
physician's Lieutenant-Colonel John

01:12:39.640 --> 01:12:45.110 position:56%
McCrea to write the most famous
poem of the war, In Flanders Fields.

01:12:45.110 --> 01:12:47.250
With McCrea's permission
the poem was used

01:12:47.250 --> 01:12:50.010
to sell war bonds in
Canada and elsewhere.

01:12:50.010 --> 01:12:52.910
It inspired the symbolism
of the poppy as a means

01:12:52.910 --> 01:12:55.000
of keeping faith with
those who died.

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:58.000
Which remained central to memorial
efforts through the present day.

01:13:00.080 --> 01:13:02.710
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: McCrea's
poem had an even greater impact

01:13:02.710 --> 01:13:05.960
in the United States
than it did in Canada.

01:13:05.960 --> 01:13:09.530
It first appeared in 1916 but it
wasn't until the following year

01:13:09.530 --> 01:13:12.020
that it took hold with the public.

01:13:12.020 --> 01:13:15.120
Reprinted in almost
every American newspaper,

01:13:15.120 --> 01:13:23.050
the poem inspired nearly 70
settings between 1917 and 1922.

01:13:23.050 --> 01:13:28.280
Composers ranged from a LaCrosse
housewife, Mrs. Percy Lloyd Cilley

01:13:28.280 --> 01:13:31.870
to the internationally known
pianist Josef Hoffmann.

01:13:31.870 --> 01:13:35.020
From Denver piano teacher Dolsey
Grossmyer [assumed spelling]

01:13:35.020 --> 01:13:38.880
to Boston composer Arthur Foote.

01:13:38.880 --> 01:13:42.320
Nearly all these settings
share one characteristic.

01:13:42.320 --> 01:13:47.220
They are among the very best music
that their creators ever made.

01:13:47.220 --> 01:13:50.070
The demographic breadth
of the composers

01:13:50.070 --> 01:13:51.700 position:56%
and the deep feelings they attempted

01:13:51.700 --> 01:13:57.270 position:56%
to express make the settings
collectively a final impassioned cry

01:13:57.270 --> 01:13:59.880
from America's Progressives.

01:13:59.880 --> 01:14:01.870
They are truly remarkable.

01:14:01.870 --> 01:14:09.090
The first recorded performance was
in Vancouver on March 28, 1917.

01:14:09.090 --> 01:14:15.450
Of a setting by John Deane Wells,
an expatriate Australian organist

01:14:15.450 --> 01:14:18.970
that was published
separately in Canada, England,

01:14:18.970 --> 01:14:23.550
and the United States and
went through four editions.

01:14:23.550 --> 01:14:27.360
The second performance
was on April 15, 1917,

01:14:27.360 --> 01:14:30.700
of a setting by Charles Ives.

01:14:30.700 --> 01:14:34.070
It was not nearly so successful.

01:14:34.070 --> 01:14:37.840
Sousa's setting probably was
heard most frequently simply

01:14:37.840 --> 01:14:40.170
because his band played it on tour.

01:14:40.170 --> 01:14:46.370 position:56%
On April 14, 1918 Frederick Donaghey
noted in the Chicago Tribune

01:14:46.370 --> 01:14:50.840
that four settings of In Flanders
Fields had been heard recently.

01:14:50.840 --> 01:14:54.130
One by Sousa, two others
by the Chicagoans,

01:14:54.130 --> 01:14:58.330
Susan Weare Hubbard,
and Alfred Hiles Bergen.

01:14:58.330 --> 01:15:01.550
And the fourth by Frank E. Tours.

01:15:01.550 --> 01:15:04.750
Tours was English by birth.

01:15:04.750 --> 01:15:09.600
From a musical family, educated at
the Royal College of Music, London.

01:15:09.600 --> 01:15:12.030
He conducted and wrote
operettas and musicals.

01:15:12.030 --> 01:15:13.990
And in 1910 he came to the States.

01:15:13.990 --> 01:15:18.220
For the next 15 years he was
active on both sides of the ocean.

01:15:18.220 --> 01:15:22.820
But he became an American
citizen on October 2,1917.

01:15:22.820 --> 01:15:25.440
And increasingly his
career was concentrated

01:15:25.440 --> 01:15:29.260
in the U.S. His setting
is remarkable.

01:15:29.260 --> 01:15:31.440
Very unlike his music for shows.

01:15:31.440 --> 01:15:35.420
And it was taken up by John
McCormack who first performed it

01:15:35.420 --> 01:15:39.930
at Carnegie Hall on
Easter Sunday, 1918.

01:15:39.930 --> 01:15:45.920 position:56%
We have then an Englishman's setting
of a Canadian's poem performed

01:15:45.920 --> 01:15:50.320
by an Irishman in a
New York concert hall.

01:15:50.320 --> 01:15:54.670
Again, a perfect example of the
musical alliance that was firmly

01:15:54.670 --> 01:15:57.000
in place by the final
months of the war.

01:16:06.510 --> 01:19:42.510
[ Music ]

01:19:42.510 --> 01:19:53.810
[ Applause ]

01:19:53.810 --> 01:19:55.250
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford:
The armistice,

01:19:55.250 --> 01:19:59.350
signed in a French railway carriage
in the early hours of November 11,

01:19:59.350 --> 01:20:04.200
1918 came into effect at
11 a.m. Paris local time.

01:20:04.200 --> 01:20:08.300
And with it, an end to
the formal hostilities.

01:20:08.300 --> 01:20:13.380
The negotiation as to the terms
of the peace were to follow.

01:20:13.380 --> 01:20:15.850
In Britain the news spread rapidly.

01:20:15.850 --> 01:20:19.470
But even on this day of
wide jubilation and relief,

01:20:19.470 --> 01:20:22.820
death hovered in new guises.

01:20:22.820 --> 01:20:26.240
The flu epidemic which was
to wipe out vast numbers

01:20:26.240 --> 01:20:29.140
of the population world
wide had already taken hold

01:20:29.140 --> 01:20:31.350
in Britain that spring.

01:20:31.350 --> 01:20:34.140
It soon intensified
bringing more grief

01:20:34.140 --> 01:20:36.480
to families in the months to come.

01:20:36.480 --> 01:20:41.660
The disease often carried home from
the trenches by returning Tommys.

01:20:41.660 --> 01:20:43.660 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee: The last
year of the war saw the introduction

01:20:43.660 --> 01:20:45.210
of conscription in Canada.

01:20:45.210 --> 01:20:48.200
Which resulted in violent
deadly riots within Quebec

01:20:48.200 --> 01:20:50.880
as French-Canadian citizens
took to the streets.

01:20:50.880 --> 01:20:54.440
The post war era witnessed a new
low in English-French relations

01:20:54.440 --> 01:20:56.400
that would fuel separatist
sentiments

01:20:56.400 --> 01:20:58.410
for the rest of the century.

01:20:58.410 --> 01:21:02.020
Meanwhile, monuments to the
60,000 Canadian soldiers who died

01:21:02.020 --> 01:21:05.490
in the conflict and
the more than 130,000

01:21:05.490 --> 01:21:08.570
who were injured were erected
throughout Europe as symbols

01:21:08.570 --> 01:21:10.000
of Canada's dedication
and sacrifice.

01:21:13.070 --> 01:21:14.370 position:56%
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: Wilson had argued

01:21:14.370 --> 01:21:18.200
that the war would make the
world safe for democracy.

01:21:18.200 --> 01:21:20.400
And in negotiating the
Treaty of Versailles.

01:21:20.400 --> 01:21:23.740
And proposing a visionary League
of Nations as an instrument

01:21:23.740 --> 01:21:26.130
to preserve peace, he attempted

01:21:26.130 --> 01:21:29.810
to extend a Progressive political
agenda to the world as a whole.

01:21:29.810 --> 01:21:33.530
But he suffered a stroke.

01:21:33.530 --> 01:21:36.260
The Treaty and the League
went down to defeat.

01:21:36.260 --> 01:21:39.410
And the Progressives
lost the 1920 election.

01:21:39.410 --> 01:21:43.200
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: In the
1920s Britain attempted to reach

01:21:43.200 --> 01:21:46.990
out to Europe with international
veteran's organizations,

01:21:46.990 --> 01:21:50.210
economic alliances
and social action.

01:21:50.210 --> 01:21:53.290
It had its place at the League of
Nations, which was up and running

01:21:53.290 --> 01:21:56.050
without the United States.

01:21:56.050 --> 01:21:59.450
Though it aimed to prevent future
world conflict the League was

01:21:59.450 --> 01:22:01.990
to prove incapable of
stopping the aggressions

01:22:01.990 --> 01:22:05.710 position:56%
from Germany and Italy in the 1930s.

01:22:05.710 --> 01:22:08.460
Meanwhile, anxiety about
the prospect of another war

01:22:08.460 --> 01:22:11.250
against France remained
high in Britain.

01:22:11.250 --> 01:22:13.320
And its relations with both Germany

01:22:13.320 --> 01:22:16.710
and the U.S. were tended
to with care.

01:22:16.710 --> 01:22:18.450
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee: Canada
signed the Treaty of Versailles

01:22:18.450 --> 01:22:20.520
as an independent sovereign nation.

01:22:20.520 --> 01:22:23.420
And served as a founding member
of the League of Nations.

01:22:23.420 --> 01:22:25.740
As one Canadian commentator
described it,

01:22:25.740 --> 01:22:30.580 position:56%
"The next great achievement of the
human society heralded by the League

01:22:30.580 --> 01:22:33.770
of Nations in all its
ramifications is what I venture

01:22:33.770 --> 01:22:35.810
to call nothing less
than the beginnings

01:22:35.810 --> 01:22:39.440
of a new international
civilization."

01:22:41.010 --> 01:22:44.610
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: The United
States was having none of this.

01:22:44.610 --> 01:22:48.070
It refused to join
international organizations.

01:22:48.070 --> 01:22:50.510
It sealed its borders.

01:22:50.510 --> 01:22:53.530 position:56%
And it severely limited immigration.

01:22:53.530 --> 01:22:58.070
It removed many of the mechanisms
that had been put in place

01:22:58.070 --> 01:23:03.850
to regulate the economy and to care
for the country's underclasses.

01:23:03.850 --> 01:23:08.890
Racism, lynching, and
bigotry surged.

01:23:08.890 --> 01:23:11.270
The rich got richer.

01:23:11.270 --> 01:23:13.900
Nine years later an overheated,

01:23:13.900 --> 01:23:17.340
underregulated economy
would plunge the country

01:23:17.340 --> 01:23:20.250
into the Great Depression.

01:23:20.250 --> 01:23:23.390
&gt;&gt; Christina Bashford: In 1930s
Britain, problems mounted.

01:23:23.390 --> 01:23:25.630
Unemployment forged
to unheard of levels

01:23:25.630 --> 01:23:29.650
as the U.S. crash impacted
the U.K. In India,

01:23:29.650 --> 01:23:34.320 position:56%
civil disobedience campaigns set off
alarms in the British government.

01:23:34.320 --> 01:23:36.880
But the deepest consternation
arose from awareness

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:39.830
of what was happening in Germany.

01:23:39.830 --> 01:23:43.380
Still sore at its treatment by the
terms of the Treaty of Versailles,

01:23:43.380 --> 01:23:45.390
Germany and Hitler
was rearming itself

01:23:45.390 --> 01:23:48.110
and expanding its territories.

01:23:48.110 --> 01:23:52.010
British policy, which above all
else, sought to avoid the slaughter

01:23:52.010 --> 01:23:54.840
of another war was
one of appeasement.

01:23:54.840 --> 01:23:58.680
And it was popular with a fair
segment of the population.

01:23:58.680 --> 01:24:04.420
In September 1938, the Conservative
Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain,

01:24:04.420 --> 01:24:07.050
along with the French Prime
Minister signed an agreement

01:24:07.050 --> 01:24:10.070
with Hitler permitting
his recent invasion

01:24:10.070 --> 01:24:13.120
of German speaking Czechoslovakia.

01:24:13.120 --> 01:24:17.990
Chamberlain came home falsely
believing it guaranteed peace

01:24:17.990 --> 01:24:19.290
for our time.

01:24:19.290 --> 01:24:22.130
&gt;&gt; Gayle Sherwood Magee:
In 1931, Canada, Australia,

01:24:22.130 --> 01:24:25.110
and New Zealand became
independent nations with control

01:24:25.110 --> 01:24:28.730
over their militaries through
the Statute of Westminster.

01:24:28.730 --> 01:24:30.030
It made no difference.

01:24:30.030 --> 01:24:32.830
In September 1939, when
Britain declared war

01:24:32.830 --> 01:24:35.050
on Germany, Canada followed suit.

01:24:35.050 --> 01:24:37.980
More than a million Canadian
fought in the second World War

01:24:37.980 --> 01:24:43.000
and nearly 100,000
died or were wounded.

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:46.150
&gt;&gt; William Brooks: Charles
Ives saw most of this coming.

01:24:46.150 --> 01:24:51.000
And he lived long enough to witness
the tragic sequel of World War II.

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:55.000
In the aftermath of
the 1920 election,

01:24:55.000 --> 01:24:58.880
he wrote a bitter indictment
of the American retreat

01:24:58.880 --> 01:25:04.230
from progressive thought
setting his own text to music.

01:25:04.230 --> 01:25:09.550
His lyrics are a litany of
ills that resonate still today.

01:25:09.550 --> 01:25:15.180 position:56%
Money interfering with democracy,
an electorate led by headlines only,

01:25:15.180 --> 01:25:17.780
politicians that distort the truth.

01:25:17.780 --> 01:25:24.700
But at the end he reaffirms
his faith, Progressivism,

01:25:24.700 --> 01:25:28.330
belief in the freedom
and dignity of all,

01:25:28.330 --> 01:25:34.920
and a society that promotes
the welfare of all will return.

01:25:34.920 --> 01:25:40.620
Ives was, eventually, proven right.

01:25:40.620 --> 01:25:41.940
Progressivism did return.

01:25:41.940 --> 01:25:44.000
And it will return again.

